 as an occupational name for a servant at a monastery or an ironic nickname for someone of monkish behavior or appearance. Compare   Lemoine  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lemoine","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Emile, Normand, Jacques, Jean-Pierre, Lucien, Pierre, Aime, Clovis, Gaston, Marcel.","French: from Old French <i>moine</i> monk (from Latin <i>monacus</i>), with fused masculine definite article <i>le</i>, probably an occupational name for a servant at a monastery or an ironic nickname for someone of monkish behavior or appearance. Compare   Lemoyne   and   Moine  .","History: This surname is listed (in the form <i>Le Moine</i>) in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors (along with its variant or altered form <i>Le Moyne</i>) and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America. — In North America, this surname was originally also a secondary surname or <i>dit</i> (‘also called’) name, now found e.g. among the descendants of Jean Guyon du Buisson from France (see   Guyon  ), through Joseph Guyon <i>dit</i> Lemoine."]},{"name":"Moinet","meanings":["(2010: NA)","French: diminutive of   Moine   ‘monk’. Compare   Monet  ."]},{"name":"Moniot","meanings":["French:","from Old French <i>moniot</i>, a diminutive of <i>moine</i> ‘monk’ (see   Moine  ).","from a shortened pet form of   Simon   or another personal name ending in <i>-mon</i>, such as <i>Aymon</i> (see   Aymond  )."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"le","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Lewis   or respelling of   Lou  , as borne by the impresario  Lew Grade  (  1906–98 , originally  Louis Winogradsky )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":1,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":36,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":67,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir William le Moigne was born about 1223, in Great Easton, Essex, England as the son of Ralph Moigne. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1295, in Gloucestershire, England, at the age of 73."},"et":{"about 1223–1295":"umbes 1223–1295","1223–1295":"1223–1295","1255–1315":"1255–1315","1200–1295":"1200–1295","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1224":"1224","1223":"1223","1200":"1200","1255":"1255","1295":"1295","about 1223":"umbes 1223","about 1295":"umbes 1295","1290":"1290","Great Easton, Essex, England":"Great Easton, Essex, England","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England"},"fi"